<datafield ind1=" " ind2=" " tag="545">
<subfield code="a">
Linda LaMacchia spent 15 months in 1995-1996 conducting her dissertation research for the University of Wisconsin, Madison, in the northwest Himalaya mountains in Dehra Dun and Dharmsala and in remote sections of Kinnaur district in the Indian state of Himachal Pradesh. She interviewed Kinnaur district nuns (jomos) belonging to one of three Tibetan Buddist sects (Drukpa Kagyu, Gelug, and Nyingma). The older nuns could still remember life in Tibet; the younger nuns had never seen Tibet. The younger nuns could speak some Hindi, enabling Linda to interview them herself. Linda used translators with the nuns who spoke only Kinnauri or Tibetan. In addition to life histories, Linda collected songs in the Kinnauri language from younger nuns as well as older Tibetan language songs.
</subfield>
</datafield>
<datafield ind1=" " ind2=" " tag="546">
<subfield code="a">
Interviews in English, Hindi, Tibetan, and Kinnauri vernacular languages; with texts and transcriptions in English, Hindi, and Tibetan.
</subfield>
</datafield>
